on of everyday life, is the first full account of Los Angeles's black community in the half century before World War II. Filled with moving human drama, it brings alive a time and place largely ignored by historians until now, detailing African American community life and political activism during the city's transformation from small town to sprawling metropolis. Writing with a novelist's sensitivity to language and drawing from fresh historical research, Douglas Flamming takes us from Reconstruction to the Jim Crow era, through the Great Migration, the Roaring Twenties, the Great Depression, and the build-up to World War II. Along the way, he offers rich descriptions of the community and its middle-class leadership, the women who were front and center with men in the battle against racism in the American West. In addition to drawing a vivid portrait of a little-known era, Flamming shows that the history of race in Los Angeles is crucial for our understanding of race in America. The civil rights activism in Los Angeles laid the foundation for critical developments in the second half of the century that continue to influence us to this day.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAfrican AmericansxCivil rightszCaliforniazLos AngelesxHistory. 0aAfrican AmericanszCaliforniazLos AngelesxHistoryy19th century. 0aAfrican AmericanszCaliforniazLos AngelesxHistoryy20th century. 0aCivil rights movementszCaliforniazLos AngelesxHistoryy19th century. 0aCivil rights movementszCaliforniazLos AngelesxHistoryy20th century. 0aCommunity lifezCaliforniazLos AngelesxHistoryy19th century. 0aCommunity lifezCaliforniazLos AngelesxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / United States / General.2bisacsh  a20th century african american history.  a20th century american history.  aafrican americans.  aamerican we